 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Botreaux was born about 1172, in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom as the son of William de Botreaux. He married Sibella Mrs Boterell before 1200, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. He died about 1220, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 50."},"et":{"Abt 1172–Abt 1220":"umbes 1172–umbes 1220","1135–Male":"1135–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1172–1220":"1172–1220","1173–Female":"1173–Surnud","1175–1199":"1175–1199","1177–Female":"1177–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1206–Male":"1206–Surnud","1212–1275":"1212–1275","1217–1273":"1217–1273","1135–1209":"1135–1209","1 October 1217":"1. oktoober 1217","before 1200":"enne 1200","1275":"1275","1220":"1220","1175":"1175","1273":"1273","1173":"1173","1172":"1172","1170":"1170","1217":"1217","1206":"1206","Abt 1172":"umbes 1172","about 1206":"umbes 1206","1212":"1212","1135":"1135","1200":"1200","Abt 1220":"umbes 1220","1177":"1177","1199":"1199","1209":"1209","Europe":"Europe","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1172–Abt 1220":"noin 1172–noin 1220","1135–Male":"1135–Kuollut","1170–Male":"1170–Kuollut","1172–1220":"1172–1220","1173–Female":"1173–Kuollut","1175–1199":"1175–1199","1177–Female":"1177–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1206–Male":"1206–Kuo